name: Kingston Fury KF432C16BBK2/16
description:
Once the most popular RAM, which for a long time came out under the flags of HyperX Fury, but changed its sign after the purchase of the HyperX brand by giant Hewlett-Packard. Thanks to the use of selected memory chips, high-quality heat sinks and high quality control, this memory has gained a reputation as a reliable and serious memory with good overclocking potential. The Fury Beast DDR4 2x8Gb module kit is highly compatible and can work in any configuration based on Intel Core and AMD Ryzen processors.

It consists of two single-sided 8-chip modules (2x8 GB) with standard CL16 timings and support for XMP technology with built-in memory overclocking profiles. The declared high clock frequency (3200 MHz) provides an impressive bandwidth and a significant increase in speed compared to classic DDR4 2400 modules. For stable operation under intense load, there is passive cooling in the form of a metal radiator that covers the memory chips. To preserve heredity, Kingston designers did not change anything at all in appearance, so the trims look almost the same as their predecessors in the HyperX Fury series.

name: Kingston Fury KF432C16BB1K2/32
description:
An overclocker kit of two DDR4 RAM modules with an impressive volume of 32 GB (2x16 GB). The manufacturer is positioning itself as a product of the middle price category of 2021, aimed at enthusiasts and gamers. Before HP bought the HyperX brand, this memory came out as part of the HyperX Fury line and was especially loved by gamers due to the combination of high quality, decent overclocking potential and affordable prices.

The kit has a standard timing scheme for DDR4 memory (CL16-18-18), there is support for XMP profiles on board. The clock frequency declared by the manufacturer of 3200 MHz allows to develop a bandwidth of up to 26.6 Gbps per module. This performance will be optimal for most mid-range gaming and work builds that don't need the extreme performance of DDR5 memory. An important element of the Kingston Fury Beast DDR4 2x16Gb is a compact aluminum heat sink, which will reliably prevent overheating when operating at higher clock frequencies and increased voltage. Thanks to the effective cooling of the memory chips, the user can manually increase the memory clock speed and increase the voltage, thereby increasing the performance of the RAM.

name: Kingston Fury KF436C16RB1K2/32
description:
Purebred overclocking memory that costs adequate money and does not fail when it matters. Part of the 2021 Kingston Fury Renegade title line. It consists of two overclocked sticks with a capacity of 16 GB each with a nominal clock frequency of 3600 MHz (throughput of 28800 MB / s), CL16 latency and an operating voltage within 1.35 V. Thanks to selected memory chips, the modules have excellent overclocking potential, which will be highly appreciated by enthusiasts and demanding gamers.

In particular, this kit is capable of overclocking to 4000 - 4266 MHz, and this is already extremely close to the performance of expensive DDR5 memory. To unleash the full potential of this memory, you need a high-end motherboard with a powerful power subsystem, a flagship chipset and support for XMP technology. For effective cooling, both trims feature an aggressive metallic black heatsink with the Fury logo that visually echoes the styling of the once-popular HyperX Predator line. It copes well with memory cooling during overclocking and rarely gets above 55°C. This kit does not include backlighting, but in general it is quite common in the series.

name: G.Skill F4-3200C16D-16GTZ
description:
A stylish kit consisting of a pair of high-speed overclocker RAM modules with a total capacity of 16 GB (2x8 GB), which is able to work stably with an effective clock frequency of 3200 MHz and lower timings. A striking exterior design can be chosen from six variants with different radiator colours. The manufacturer is positioned as a product of the upper price category of 2016, aimed at modding enthusiasts, overclocker enthusiasts and gamers.

The modules of the G.Skill Trident Z DDR4 2x8Gb F4-3200C16D-16GTZ kit are designed for installation in multi-purpose home and gaming systems. Can be used as part of inexpensive workstations. By default, the modules work with an effective clock frequency of 2133 MHz, timings 19-19-19-43 and a voltage of 1.2 V. To automatically activate the claimed performance mode (3200 MHz in dual-channel mode with CL16-16-16-36 timings at a voltage of 1 .35 V) requires a motherboard that supports XMP 2.0 technology. If the motherboard does not support this technology, then the necessary parameters can be configured manually in the corresponding section of the UEFI BIOS. The performance mode provides high bandwidth (25.6 Gbps), sufficient for any games and applications. Claimed compatible with platforms based on 6th to 12th generation Intel Core CPUs and AMD Ryzen CPUs.

name: Kingston Fury KF436C17BBK2/16
description:
A dual-channel set of DDR4 RAM modules that can work stably with an effective clock frequency of 3600 MHz. It consists of two single-sided (peer-to-peer) modules with a volume of 8 GB each (16 GB in total). The manufacturer is positioned as a product of the middle price category, aimed at demanding gamers and enthusiasts who can get the maximum performance from the available hardware.

Designed for use in high-performance multi-purpose home and gaming systems. Thanks to the claimed high clock frequency of 3200 MHz, it provides high throughput up to 28.6 Gbps. The Kingston Fury Beast DDR4 2x8Gb KF436C17BBK2/16 RAM Module Kit is highly compatible and can work stably in configurations based on Intel Core (6th to 12th generation) CPUs, as well as AMD Ryzen (Zen/Zen2) CPUs.

/zen3). During the initial installation, the modules operate in the default mode (DDR4-2133 with CL15-15-15-35 timings at 1.2 V). To automatically activate the claimed speed mode (DDR4-3600 with CL17-17-21 at 1.35V), the motherboard must support XMP 2.0 technology. Otherwise, the configuration can be done manually by changing the settings in the UEFI BIOS. Asymmetrical, low-profile aluminium heatsinks provide heat dissipation.

name: GOODRAM IR-X3200D464L16SA/16GDC
description:
Fast DDR4 RAM capable of running at 3200 MHz out of the box. It is a representative of the IRDM gaming line from the Polish brand GOODRAM, which in just a few years has become a serious competitor to popular RAM series from Kingston, Corsair and other famous brands. The decisive factor in the success of this series was the desire of the manufacturer to reduce the cost of production, while not sacrificing quality and speed.

The GOODRAM IRDM X DDR4 2x8Gb kit consists of a pair of dual-channel DDR4 RAM modules with a capacity of 8 GB each. For both, the optimal operating frequency by the standards of 2022 is 3200 MHz with a standard latency of CL16 at a nominal voltage of 1.35 V. GOODRAM takes a responsible approach to the selection of memory chips, so all representatives of this family have a good overclocking potential.

Unfortunately, there is no support for XMP profiles, so any changes in memory performance must be made manually in the BIOS of the motherboard. To avoid overheating, the board and memory modules are almost completely covered by an aluminum heatsink with the Iridium logo and an interesting texture. The heatsinks are offered in several color options, so users can choose the design of the RAM based on the color of the case or the tone of the backlight.

name: G.Skill F4-3200C16D-16GIS
description:
A dual-channel set consisting of two high-frequency RAM modules with a total capacity of 16 GB (2x8 GB). It is the top model in the 2019 G.Skill Aegis product line. It features stable operation at 3200 MHz, balanced timings and stylish exterior design. It is positioned as a product of the middle price category, aimed at a wide range of gaming enthusiasts and low-cost-conscious overclocking enthusiasts.

G.Skill Aegis DDR4 2x8Gb F4-3200C16D-16GIS kit modules are recommended for use in multi-purpose home and gaming systems. Perfect for an inexpensive workstation. The manufacturer guarantees compatibility with platforms based on Intel Core CPUs (6th to 12th generation) and AMD Ryzen (Zen/Zen2/Zen3) processors. For simplified automatic activation of the claimed performance mode with a frequency of 3200 MHz (timings CL16-18-18-38, voltage 1.35 V), a motherboard with support for XMP 2.0 technology is required (otherwise, the necessary parameters are configured manually in the UEFI BIOS). The performance mode provides a high throughput (25.6 Gbps), sufficient for any games and resource-intensive applications.

name: G.Skill F5-6000J3636F16GX2-TZ5RK
description:
A dual-channel set of DDR5 RAM modules, which hit stores for the first time only at the end of 2021 and so far remains a niche product. This technique is designed for owners of flagship gaming PCs, overclocking enthusiasts and owners of workstations equipped with rather expensive motherboards that support DDR5 and XMP 3.0 standards. By doubling the memory blocks, increasing the pulse duration and increasing the number of independent subchannels, the speed capabilities of the DDR5 format are significantly superior to the current DDR4.

For example, this kit immediately starts up at a frequency of 6000 MHz (with timings 38-38-38) and guarantees a throughput of 48,000 MB / s. And this is actually 2 times faster than most predecessors to the Trident family. Otherwise, G.Skill Trident Z5 RGB DDR5 2x16Gb supports the new XMP 3.0 overclocking specification and is equipped with a built-in ODECC error correction algorithm, which improves stability at extreme speeds. To reduce the heating level, the strips are equipped with multi-coloured metal radiators that effectively cool the chips and the memory controller, and also perform a decorative function due to the built-in backlight with the ability to synchronize.

name: Kingston Fury KF432C16BBAK2/16
description:
A set of RAM modules with DDR4-3200 with a spectacular controllable RGB LED backlight. Prior to HP's purchase of the HyperX brand, this memory was branded HyperX Fury and regularly received high marks from the press and buyers due to its low price, high quality and good overclocking potential. It is a product of the middle price category, focused on use in gaming PCs with an abundance of backlighting and entry-level workstations based on Intel and AMD processors.

The Kingston Fury Beast RGB DDR4 2x8Gb kit consists of two 8 GB memory modules with a declared clock speed of 3200 MHz and a bandwidth of around 25600 MB / s. It runs out of the box in DDR4-2400 mode with standard CL16 timings (16-18-18) and voltage of 1.2 V. To install the modes declared by the manufacturer, you need a motherboard that supports XMP profiles with pre-selected timings and voltage.

Or manual memory overclocking directly in the BIOS. For stable operation under intense load, both brackets are equipped with jet-black metal heatsinks that effectively cool the chips and the memory controller. A translucent light guide is fixed at the end, and RGB LEDs shine through it, which can be synchronized with the rest of the backlight in the case. The height of the bars is 41.2 mm, and this factor must be taken into account during assembly so that the combs do not rest against the processor cooler during the installation of the RAM.

name: Kingston Fury KF436C16RB1AK2/32
description:
A set of dual-rank DDR4-3600 high-speed RAM modules with controllable RGB LED backlighting. It consists of a pair of double-sided modules with a total capacity of 32 GB (2x16 GB). The manufacturer is positioned as a product of the upper price category in 2021, designed for demanding gamers, modding enthusiasts and enthusiasts. Designed for installation in multi-purpose home and gaming systems.

It can become an important part of a spectacular demonstration personal computer. The claimed high clock speed delivers an impressive 28.8 Gbps of bandwidth, which has the most positive impact on overall computing and gaming performance. The Kingston Fury Renegade RGB DDR4 2x16Gb RAM Module Kit has a high degree of compatibility and is able to work in a wide range of configurations based on Intel Core processors (from 6th to 12th generation), as well as AMD Ryzen processors (Zen / Zen2 / Zen3 ). Extreme Memory Profile (XMP 2.0) technology is supported for fast automatic timing adjustment. Dynamic RGB effects powered by Infrared Sync Technology provide smooth backlight synchronization.

name: Kingston Fury KF436C18BBK2/32
description:
A dual-channel high-speed DDR4 RAM kit, the modules of which are guaranteed to work stably at a clock frequency of 3600 MHz. It consists of two peer-to-peer sticks with a volume of 16 GB each (2x16 GB). The manufacturer is positioned as a product of the upper price category, aimed at demanding gamers and enthusiasts who can achieve maximum performance by fine-tuning the operating modes of the main system components.

The Kingston Fury Beast DDR4 2x16Gb RAM kit is designed for use in high-performance universal home and gaming systems. Its significant volume is sufficient for comfortable gaming in any AAA titles of 2012-2022, streaming, parallel video capture, voice chats and other typical tasks. Thanks to the high clock frequency, high throughput up to 28.8 Gbps is provided. It is also worth noting the presence of low-profile aluminium heatsinks, support for XMP 2.0 technology, as well as the ability to work stably in configurations based on Intel Core (6th to 12th generation) and AMD Ryzen (Zen/Zen2/Zen3) CPUs.

name: Patriot Memory PVS416G320C6K
description:
A dual-channel set of DDR4 RAM modules capable of guaranteed operation with an effective clock frequency of 3200 MHz. Consists of 2 single-sided modules with a volume of 8 GB each (total 16 GB). The manufacturer is positioned as a product of the middle price category, aimed at demanding gamers and enthusiasts who can get the maximum performance from the available hardware. Designed for installation in performant multi-purpose home and gaming systems.

Thanks to the claimed high clock frequency of 3200 MHz, it demonstrates high throughput up to 25.6 Gbps. When installed, the modules operate in default DDR4-2133 mode with CL15-15-15-35 timings at 1.2V. board with full support for XMP 2.0 technology. If there is no XMP support, then the configuration can be performed manually by setting the appropriate parameters in the UEFI BIOS. The set of RAM modules Patriot Memory Viper Steel DDR4 2x8Gb PVS416G320C6K has a high degree of compatibility and is able to work in configurations based on Intel Core CPUs (6th to 12th generation), as well as AMD Ryzen CPUs (Zen / Zen2 / Zen3). For stable operation in overclocking, there is a passive cooling radiator.

name: G.Skill F4-3200C16D-16GVKB
description:
A dual-channel set of fast DDR4 RAM capable of guaranteed operation at an effective clock speed of 3200 MHz. Consists of two modules with a volume of 8 GB each. Designed for use in high-performance personal computers based on the Intel Core platform (from 6th to 12th generation) or in configurations based on AMD Ryzen processors. 16 GB of memory is enough for most professional applications and all popular gaming projects in 2011-2021.

The G.Skill Ripjaws V DDR4 2x8Gb RAM kit is positioned as a mid-range product aimed at gamers and enthusiasts who can get an additional performance boost through overclocking. Supports Intel XMP 2.0 technology. On motherboards that do not support this technology, the modules will work in the default mode (DDR4-2133, timings CL15-15-15 at 1.2 V). In this case, to set high passport specifications (DDR4-3200, CL16-18-18 timings at 1.35 V), you will need to manually configure a number of fine UEFI BIOS settings. Both modules are equipped with low-profile aluminium heatsinks, which can be useful for further overclocking, especially when the supply voltage is increased. The increased height of the modules (42 mm) must be taken into account when installing large CPU air coolers.

name: Kingston Fury KF432S20IB/8
description:
Representative of the Kingston Impact series, which includes SO-DIMM DDR4 strips designed for owners of powerful laptops and miniature computers. This model replaced the HyperX Impact RAM, which passed into the hands of Kingston after a deal between HyperX and HP. The Kingston Fury Impact DDR4 1x8Gb module has 8 GB of memory with a claimed clock speed of 3200 MHz and a throughput of around 25600 MB/s.

It runs out of the box with standard CL20 timings (20-22-22) and a voltage of 1.2 V. The manufacturer guarantees full compatibility with the latest generations of Intel and AMD processors. Kingston assured that for the updated version they finalized the power circuits, redid the element base and used more modern memory chips. This made it possible to achieve higher throughput at lower temperatures.

Unlike other laptop memory, which is usually bought on a buy-and-forget basis, it looks as serious as possible. For example, this is a rare series of SO-DIMM RAM, in which absolutely all memory modules are covered with thermal stickers, the maximum clock frequency during overclocking can reach 3200 MHz, and the strips themselves support Plug N Play and XMP overclocking technologies.
